data.content:
Yes! MSTest 3.7+ supports **ValueTuple-based `DynamicData`**, which gives you type safety and named parameters instead of `object[]`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string input, bool expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:**
- `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string input, bool expected)>` — compile-time type checking, no boxing, and named tuple elements serve as documentation.
- `["valid@email.com", true]` → `("valid@email.com", true)` — tuples instead of arrays.

If you later need per-case display names, wrap with `TestDataRow<T>`:

```csharp
public static IEnumerable<TestDataRow<(string input, bool expected)>> TestData =>
[
    new(("valid@email.com", true)) { DisplayName = "Valid email" },
    new(("invalid", false))        { DisplayName = "No @ symbol" },
    new(("", false))               { DisplayName = "Empty string" },
];
```
